data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with MSTest's specialized collection assertions — they provide much better failure messages than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Original | Replacement | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "expected non-empty collection" instead of "expected True, got False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "expected 3 elements, found N" |
| `users.Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | Keep `Assert.IsTrue` for the predicate check, or filter + `Assert.ContainsSingle` | Clearer intent |

For the admin check specifically, if you want to assert exactly one admin exists:

```csharp
var admins = users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin");
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(admins); // asserts exactly 1 and returns it
Assert.AreEqual("Admin", admin.Role);      // further assertions on the element
```

`Assert.ContainsSingle` both verifies the count **and** returns the element for further inspection — no need for `Single()` + null check.
